    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The MACRS formula for the first year depreciation is a straightforward one. It's a 200% declining balance method, which is a bit like a goblin's favorite game of \"find the hidden treasure\" - you start with a full value and then subtract a percentage of it each year. \n\nFor the first year, the formula is: \n\nFirst Year Depreciation = Cost of Equipment - Residual Value\n\nBut if you're using the MACRS table, the first year depreciation is simply 100% of the cost minus the residual value. However, if you don't have the residual value, you can use the MACRS table to find the first year depreciation. \n\nLet's say your client bought the equipment for $100,000 and the residual value is $20,000. The first year depreciation would be:\n\nFirst Year Depreciation = $100,000 - $20,000 = $80,000\n\nOr, using the MACRS table, you can find the first year depreciation by looking up the equipment's cost in the table and subtracting the residual value. \n\nNow, I'm reminded of a goblin's favorite saying: \"A goblin's treasure is always hidden, but with the right formula,",
